  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-small-idk">
    <title>I Don't Know - Small Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      You stall.
    </p>

    <p>
      <q>Well<ellipsis/> it sure is lovely weather here in Anikrub today.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer laughs.
    </p>

    <p>
      <q>You statisticians.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      You realise avoidance won't help.
    </p>

    <assemblage>
      <p>
        <alert>Advice:</alert>
      </p>
      <p>
        Start by comparing average yield by variety.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then break it down by region. This should lead you to your answer
      </p>
    </assemblage>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-small-icri">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-small-locale-correct">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-small-icri-either">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-small-help">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-small-help">
    <title>Help - Small Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      Let's walk through this carefully.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Step 1:</alert> Look at overall average yield by variety. You may find that ICRI looks better overall.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Step 2:</alert> Now break the data down by region. When you look at Anikrub specifically, Local outperforms ICRI on average.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>What happened?</alert>
    </p>

    <p>
      This is an example of how aggregated data can hide regional differences. The distribution of varieties across regions affects the overall average.
    </p>

    <p>
      Never give advice based only on overall averages when context matters.
    </p>

    <p>
      For Anikrub, the correct answer is: <alert>Locale</alert>
    </p>

    <p>
      Go to <xref ref="Q2-small">Question 2</xref>.
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

</section>
